) is a Japanese multinational conglomerate corporation headquartered in Kōnan Minato, Tokyo, Japan.

The company was originally established on September 11, 1875, in Kyoto, as a retail shop for British-made merchandise. In 1881, Fusajiro Yamauchi took over the store and renamed it to Yamauchi & Co. In 1890, the company moved its headquarters to Tokyo. In 1919, the company changed its name to Nintendo Karuta Co., specializing in playing cards.

In the following years, Nintendo entered various lines of business, such as cab services, lipstick, and hanabi (fireworks). In 1963, Hiroshi Yamauchi, great-grandchild of Fusajiro Yamauchi, became company president, and in 1966, the company name was shortened to Nintendo Co., Ltd. It was during his tenure that the company entered the electronic games industry, first with the release of the electronic Love Tester in 1969, and later with arcade video games starting in 1971

